source: In this work, based on a variant of the classical Lewis (1969) signaling model, we explore the conditions for the emergence of context-dependent communication in a situated scenario.
translation: The concept of context-dependent communication is an important aspect of communication in natural languages. In the Lewis model, the meaning of an utterance is determined by the context in which it is made, and this can lead to different interpretations depending on the situation. In the scenario we study, we explore how context can modify the meaning of the utterance, and how this influence can lead to different interpretations. Our work builds on previous research in context-dependent communication, and contributes to the study of the mechanisms underlying linguistic communication.
